Carnegie Mellon University has unveiled the striking design of its new Richard King Mellon Hall of Sciences, a 338,900 square-foot building that will host researchers and students from its Mellon College of Science (MCS) and School of Computer Science (SCS). 

The new building also will house the new Institute for Contemporary Art Pittsburgh (ICA), which serves as a critical hub for art, culture and exchange. 

Sitework for the $252 million project is slated to begin in the first quarter of 2024 in Pittsburgh’s Oakland neighborhood, at the intersection of Forbes Avenue and South Craig Street.

Visit our link in bio to learn more.

On #VeteransDay, our nation recognizes military service members, past and present, for dedicating their lives to protecting our personal freedoms and preserving democracy around the world.

At Carnegie Mellon, our military community on campus comprises more than 250 staff, faculty and students, and includes our Veterans Alliance Employee Resource Group and NROTC. These veterans, active-duty service members and cadets join an untold number of CMU alumni who have served.

First lady Jill Biden and acting Secretary of Labor Julie Su traveled to Carnegie Mellon University's Mill 19 on Wednesday to convene members of a Pittsburgh Workforce Hub and announce commitments to create and expand pathways into good-paying jobs for the region.

Biden started things off by making a new friend.

“Before I start, I just have to touch that robot!” Biden said, examining a blue Yaskawa MOTOMAN GP50 industrial robot used by Carnegie Mellon professor Chiang Liu on display at Mill 19.

#pittsburgh

Carnegie Mellon University has started its historic journey to the moon!

Iris, a tiny, lightweight lunar rover built by CMU students, and MoonArk, a collaborative sculpture project led by faculty, students and alumni, left Pittsburgh on Friday morning en route to their launch pad in Florida. But first, members of the team had a chance to say goodbye and pose for photographs in front of a scale model of the rocket that will take Iris into space.

The projects are scheduled to launch to the moon on Sunday, Dec. 24.

Carnegie Mellon University and the Norman and Ruth Rales Foundation are thrilled to announce today a new initiative to increase access to graduate education in STEM fields for underrepresented and under-resourced students.

With a transformative gift from the Rales Foundation, the $150 million CMU Rales Fellows Program will help cultivate a new generation of domestic national STEM leaders. The program will eliminate cost as a barrier to select master’s degree and Ph.D. programs for these students and support them through a distinctive, holistic ecosystem of developmental and networking opportunities to the benefit of the Fellows during their time at CMU and as they advance in their careers.

Read more about this new program at the link in our bio.
